narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned about urban development patterns in New Haven. How to examine economic patterns through architecture.

I learned about the urban environment and the built environment around me. I learned different ways of interpreting and analyzing our world, and the impact actions have on cities. I got great insights into individual pieces of New Haven life, and developed an even greater understanding of the city (and some knowledge about basic architecture)
I learned how to conduct archival research to look at the history of buildings and sites in New Haven. I also got to explore different parts of the city!

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: one of a kind class. super fun. walking tour! you get outside of the places you normally go as a yale student and meet very interesting people along the way. 
Weaknesses: it's a little chaotic, in that the guidelines for the project weren't super clear and deadlines floated. but really an awesome class

Put simply, this course is incredible. If it is offered, try try try to take it (although I don't know the next time it will be offered). It is so unique and exposes you to things outside the classroom that you would never otherwise experience. There is a great camaraderie formed in the class, and the assignments are pretty manageable. Elihu even always had a snack to give us in the middle of our 3 hour excursion. The specific TA's we had for the class were great too, especially Zach, who was just so helpful and generous with his time and knowledge.

I would shorten the class session and have a separate day, say Monday, where we present field notes to a small section. Otherwise its really easy to let this class get deprioiritized (unless you have a true burning passion for it).

I liked being able to develop the final project at my own pace; however due dates were always very unclear and misinformation is common. At the end of the day Professor Rubin and the TFs were very understanding and accommodated student needs.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments:
Yes! It'll get you to go to new places. It's basically a weekly guided tour of New Haven
The only real assignment for the course is the final project, which you do in stages throughout the semester. This project was much more fun and well-guided than the one in intro architecture. It's super flexible, and Professor Rubin and the teaching team will get behind your excitement. 
Professor Rubin is a joy, and it's so fun to experience the city alongside him.
I would wholeheartedly recommend this course. It gives you such a great insight into the city in an engaging way.
Yes!!!!! This is an amazing class -- if you have the chance to take it, do it!!
I would recommend this course to anyone who wants to explore the city of New Haven beyond the Yale bubble and critically look at the universities relationship with the city.
